headline.main: World Briefing | Asia: East Timor: More Security Means Fewer Troops

lead_paragraph: The United Nations began a six-month reduction in its peacekeeping force from its current level of 8,000 to 5,000. At a ceremony for the departure of the first group -- 264 Kenyan soldiers -- the force commander, Lt. Gen. Winai Phattiyakul, said, ''This is indicative of the great improvement in the security situation in East Timor.'' The former Portuguese colony, which was annexed by Indonesia in 1976, was ravaged by pro-Indonesia militias after voting for independence in 1999. Seth Mydans (NYT)
abstract: UN begins six-month reduction in peacekeeping force in East Timor from current level of 8,000 to 5,000 (S)
